<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<body>
<p>
Let \(T:V\to W\) be a <a knowl="defs/vec/map">linear map</a>.
</p>
<p>
The <b>kernel</b> of \(T\), denoted \(\ker T\),
is the set of all \(v\in V\) such that \(Tv = 0\).
</p>
<ul>
<li>
This forms a subspace of \(V\).
<details>
<summary>
[explanation]
</summary>
Let \(\alpha, \beta\in\mathbf F\) and \(u, v\in\ker T\).
Then
\[T(\alpha u + \beta v) = \alpha Tu + \beta Tv = 0 + 0 = 0,\]
so \(\alpha u + \beta v\in\ker T\).
</details>
</li>
<li>
The map \(T\) is injective if and only if \(\ker T = \{0\}\).
<details>
<summary>
[explanation]
</summary>
<p>
Suppose \(T\) is injective, i.e. suppose for all \(u, v\in V\)
that
\[Tu = Tv\implies u = v.\]
Let \(v\in\ker T\). Then \(Tv = 0 = T0\), which implies \(v = 0\),
so \(\ker T = \{0\}\).
</p>
<p>
Conversely, suppose \(\ker T = \{0\}\),
and let \(u, v\in V\) with \(Tu = Tv\).
Then \(T(u - v) = Tu - Tv = 0\), hence \(u - v\in\ker T\),
hence \(u - v = 0\), hence \(u = v\), so \(T\) is injective.
</p>
</details>
</li>
</ul>
</body>
</html>
